John Edward: Language Skills Necessary for the Citizens of the World
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their scientific achievements – in 2018 they were able to boast of further excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another man in a language that he understands, then it’s in his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages occupy the first place in the league rankings, with the highest dissertation rates occurring in the case of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages achieved a higher grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students had a higher grade A in Mandarin, and 72 percent of students in German, 69 percent of students in French, and 63 percent of students in Spanish also had an A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as subjects to choose from, is conducted to the same extent as learning STEM subjects (strict science, technology, engineering and mathematics) as part of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17% of job vacancies were due to a lack of language skills of candidates, according to the report.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for the start of a professional career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring language skills,
A lifelong skill like learning a second language will provide a huge advantage in the future — no matter what career path you choose.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language whose percentage of people using it was double-digit, i.e. 15%.
That is why investing in foreign language teaching is so important for today’s children.
The knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a greater chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages it teaches.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of the child, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed — no matter what the future holds for them.
Currently, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and therefore it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a great deal of choice, diversity and level.
That's just right.
John Edward, Chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
