Harvard students attend a course on adequately long-term rest
The new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, aimed at tackling the growing macho culture of learning by “caffeine-powered midnight students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course by giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now that I’m in my final year of college?’
She stated that no one ever told her about the meaning of the dream, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
During the course, which took place for the first time this year, students are explained how good sleep-related habits help to achieve good results in science and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of university health care, said the course was set to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from severe lack of sleep within a week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes a picture of a room in the academy where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects sports performance, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this will not cause an immediate change in the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know — just as everyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “full-time science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means a growing problem of lack of sleep.
Providing a sufficient amount of good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students fighting stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even avoiding weight gain, as lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course after taking part in one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of the course for the entire campus.
The next step according to him is to invite all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving on to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm that reminds them when to go to sleep and when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED lighting, which can disrupt the daily rhythm and lead to problems.
