Almanac: inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page from our publication “Sunday Morning” Almanac: September 30, 1882 — 136 years ago... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, Geiger’s counter has become both an element of science and pop culture, such as in the 1950 film “Bells of Coronado”, in which these seemingly unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans performed:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter used to locate radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you will hear the effects of atoms emitted by radioactive minerals.”
Evans: “Now you hear something!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name has survived to this day.
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “perceive” enemy cells.
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to ‘perceive’ enemy cells and destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize enemy cells as part of the treatment.
This method consists of extracting immune cells from the patient and changing them in the laboratory.
Then they can "see" the protein common to many cancers. Then they are re-injected into the body.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancers.
One woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize enemy cells was observed to have ovarian cancer disappearing for more than 18 months.
The method consists of extracting immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can “see” a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then re-injecting the patient with these cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that this vaccine works very well.”
HER2 “propels the growth of several types of cancers,” including breast, ovarian, lung and large intestine cancers, Prof. Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach, which involves taking immune cells from patients and “learning” how to locate their cancer cells, has worked in the treatment of some type of leukemia.
