HIV/AIDS: China sees 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this problem, according to the health service of this country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases were transmitted sexually, which means a change from the past.
Traditionally, the HIV virus spreads rapidly in some parts of China as a result of an infected blood transfusion.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been almost completely reduced, as Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, year on year, the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Given the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease result from insufficient protection during sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to HIV medicines as part of efforts to address the problem.
