The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet in order to compete with the platforms Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the creator of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that is set to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on the open source platform — Solid — belonging to Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of Inrupt’s creation was “domination of the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the startup.
“The historic moment has come.”
The application uses Solid platform technology to enable people to create their own “personal data online store” or otherwise POD.
It can include contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
A unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to the company’s president, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide the resources, processes and appropriate skills to help make the Solid platform available to all people.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, technology makers around the world were able to create their own decentralized applications using tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change that day by day will cause all their business models to turn upside down.
“Don’t ask for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a post on Medium on Saturday that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and the ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has done a lot in the debate on net neutrality.
Inrupt Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely excited to be thinking about the next era in network development,” Berners-Lee added.
