The memory of the only clergyman of the Church of England, who during World War I was awarded the Victoria Cross as a combatant, was celebrated 100 years later in his hometown.
Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded on 29 September 1918 for his raids on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never learning that he was awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
