According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lt. Col. Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from field units and machine guns".
He then hurried to the line of fire and with "the greatest courage" led it forward, after which he single-handedly attacked the position of the field units, eliminating three of them.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I would never manage to meet, but at the same time something humble.”
Together with his brother, Dr. James Vann, he made a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt “very honored to be able to take part in the parade” and added that “the courage of a true hero manifests itself in the support he receives from many people.”
