The National Trust is listening to the secret life of batsmen
New research conducted on estates in the Scottish Highlands aims to show how bats use the landscape when harvesting food.
The results of the study are expected to shed new light on the conservation of these unique flying mammals and help guide future actions to protect them.
The research, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will involve common and small dwarfs, as well as brown long-eared bats and bats from the family of reddish nights at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
In key locations around the estate, special recorders will be deployed to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field research using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings is aimed at determining the frequencies of signals sent by bats and the behavior of individual species.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest land for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the last century.
They are endangered by construction and development works, which have an impact on settlements and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly glue and certain chemicals used in building materials and even domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their night hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complex echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles on their way.
The NTS organization, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It is made up of ten trained experts who regularly carry out research, inspections and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization has even established the first and only dedicated bat reserve in Scotland on the property of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight out of ten Scottish bat species.
David Thompson, the landlord of the estate, says that it is the ideal territory for batsmen.
“Threave has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns about bats. The work we do here and in other estates will help us better understand what they need to grow."
It stresses the importance of controlling the presence of bats before proceeding to carry out maintenance work on the estates, because the unintentional destruction of one nest can kill up to 400 females and young people, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected —killing, harassing, or disturbing them, and destroying their nests is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish Bat Conservation Trust officer, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species, we don’t even know how their populations are doing.”
