Flowering information — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota plankton density decreases
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in plankton densification in some parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of pstrocate bloom has been reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting that its thickening is decreasing.
It stretches for about 209 kilometres along the coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
Flowers can be found about 16 kilometers off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
Flowering was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, an average concentration of plankton was recorded at the coast and in the waters of Pinellas County, low to medium at the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high at the coast and in the waters of the Sarasota County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation are still reported.
Last week, however, they were not recorded in northwestern Florida.
